<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-285-998  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 285 998.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  May 15 1989 v216 n20 p32(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sonet and BISDN: a marriage of technologies. (synchronous opticalnetwork; broadband integrated services digital network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miller, Thomas C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sonet (synchronous optical network) and ISDN (integrated servicesdigital network) were originally developed for different reasonsbut they are now being interrelated through the work of standardsbodies.andP;  When narrowband accesses developed into broadband ISDN,or BISDN, it became apparent that a standardized, high-capacitytransmission medium would help make BISDN a reality.andP;  Sonet is theobvious answer.andP;  Sonet brings the promise of a hundredfoldincrease in capacity (from 1.544M-bps to 155.52M-bps), signalingthat the information age has truly arrived.andP;  With so muchbandwidth and capacity, new applications will proliferate.andO;Services will be of two kinds: interactive (videoconferencing,video-telephony, high-speed data, E-mail with images, and databaseservices), and distributive (cable TV, high-definition cable TV,pay-per-view TV, and document distribution).andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ISDNIntegrated Voice-DataStandardizationNetworksFiber opticsFuture TechnologiesTelecommunications.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Glossary. (table)SONET ADM in terminal mode. (chart)MAN application. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>